{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f83444a9-d9db-407f-a654-7c2308bdb24c","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. MAUI has no request pipeline, so there's no natural scope boundary — `Scoped` effectively behaves like `Singleton`. Your `DbContext` lives for the entire app lifetime, which is why tracked entities persist across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — a new `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory`** for explicit lifetime control:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is generally preferred — it makes the `DbContext` lifetime explicit and keeps it short-lived, matching EF Core best practices.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ce0219c-3e61-4530-914c-850992b9e8c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so `Scoped` behaves essentially the same as `Singleton` — one instance for the entire app lifetime. That's why data \"persists\" across page navigations.","outputTokens":383,"requestId":"9541:145E6F:14ACA1A:17265EC:6A06736C"},"id":"7a8396da-4855-492b-bb57-6d5475d6f1ff","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:14:29.031Z","parentId":"f1bb3535-e521-4144-be4e-fa153a6ed26d"}
